items.name: BixMix StylizedVision
items.description:
Welcome to my personal favorite checkpoint. It's a checkpoint aimed at being anime centered with a painting/stylized theme. It's very flexible, and works great with most loras. This model does both SFW and NSFW images.

Recommended settings:

VAE:

First of all you should be using a VAE which you manually set in the settings. Download either:

https://huggingface.co/stabilityai/sd-vae-ft-mse-original/tree/main

or

https://huggingface.co/hakurei/waifu-diffusion-v1-4/blob/main/vae/kl-f8-anime2.ckpt (I use this one)

Place this file in your stable diffusion directory -> models -> VAE

Then on the webui go settings -> stable diffusion -> SD VAE and choose from the drop-down menu.

If you do not use a VAE, all your images will come out washed out and grayish.

Generation settings:

Resolution: 512x512 or 512x768 or 768x512

Steps: 30-40

Sampling method: Whatever you like best. My personal favorite is Euler a, but i also use DPM++ 2M Karras and DPM++ 2M SDE Karras

Hires.fix:

Upscaler: 4x-UltraSharp or 4x_fatal_anime_500000_G can be found in: https://upscale.wiki/wiki/Model_Database

Hires steps: 10

Denoising Strength: 0.3

Upscale by: Whatever resolution you want. I usually go 1.75

items.name: Action Poses
items.description:
For those new to ControlNet and wondering how to use these files, the best tutorial I've found is this one (reddit).

Action poses for controlnet.

In the .zip files: .png to use in openpose and depth models. Added .json for openpose too so you can make modifications to the pose file. A more accurate description of what's in the .zip file is in each version description.

I am open to suggestions for what other categories to add here.

To do list:

  • Aiming/shooting: done

  • Fighting (punching/kicking): done

  • Jumping: -

  • ...

Additional notes:

  • Use attributes like "from_behind", "from_below", "from_above", or "from_side" in your prompt to create the angles you are looking for.

  • Climbing: several of the climbing poses work well with "from_above".

  • Aiming/Shooting: SD doesn't generate hands nor guns well. I'd suggest using depth rather than openpose for aiming/shooting poses as you're at least getting an approximation of the shape of the weapon. You can also modify the depth .png in PS or paint to better approximate the shape of the character and weapon.

  • Fighting (punching/kicking): Obviously requires inpainting. Photobashing also useful to add characters (targets) to your scene.

  • Lowering the "Control Weight" and "Ending Control Step" parameters can help in creating poses that are slightly (or significantly) different from the origin pose. By my experience, for depth maps you have to go as low as 0.3 and 0.3 to see significant changes.

All pictures were generated with the Dreamshaper 7 or 8 Model.

Loras used: 3D Rendering Style (https://civitai.com/models/73756/3d-rendering-style) v1.4.1

Generation data: see attached pictures.

In the .zip file: .png for 19 poses to use in ControlNet (OpenPose and Depth). I'll be adding the .json files as soon as OpenPose Editor works again (it has been bugging ever since the latest update).

Pictures were generated with the Comimicry (https://civitai.com/models/105172?modelVersionId=119486) or MachineCode's Comic Book Style (https://civitai.com/models/71404/mcbs-machinecodes-comic-book-style).

Using the depth model is the easiest path to decent results here. May make sense to tweak the "control weight" and "ending control step" parameters for additional flexibility.

You will likely need to use inpainting to generate fight scenes between different characters.

modelVersions.name: Aiming/Shooting v1.0
modelVersions.description:
13 shooting/aiming gun poses for openpose/controlnet.

SD is bad in generating hands and guns, so you're unlikely to get a useful result through txt-img and controlnet alone.

Using the depth model is the easiest path to decent results as it at least predetermines the shape of the weapon, but takes away from flexibility. May make sense to tweak the "control weight" and "ending control step" parameters for additional flexibility.

Request or Suggestion Rule:

  1. No request for a minor!

  2. The requested should have public data (not private)

  3. Should have more than 30 good-quality images

  4. Since all requests or suggestions are free, I will still need to like your request, otherwise its a work not a hobby for me.

NOTE: I will keep updating more actresses in versions update

===

Usage Guide

--

A. Lora Weight

  • 0.1 ~ 0.4 -- is to combine multiple faces or features, or if you experience overbaking

  • 0.5 ~ 0.7 -- is a balanced weight to get still accurate features but with more flexibility

  • 0.8 ~ 1.0 -- is to create an accurate representation of the features.

B. CFG Scale

  • A lower CFG Scale means AI gets more creative and less overbaking problems.

  • A higher CFG Scale means results get very accurate with training sets and are more prone to overbaking problems.

  • Dynamic CFG Threshold, using this method allows you to bump up quality and achieve photorealistic easily, but with lycoris, I found out recently that this method actually lowers the success rate, so only use it when you are composing with a Lora / model that works fine with this method.

C. Sampling Steps, High Res Fix & Upscaling

  • I like to use sampling steps at 50, with high res steps at 20, or 1/2 of the sampling steps.

  • I find that 2M Karras works better and faster than SDE Karras. with ERSGAN 4x+ method + ERSGAN 4x for Upscaling. This method actually gives quite good results without being too sharp or too plasticky

  • Upscaling - GPFGAN @0.25, Codeformer @0.3 & Codeformer Weight @0.15 seems to yield superior results.

Enjoy.

items.name: Fizz | League of Legends | LoRA
items.description:
PLEASE NOTE: Trigger word has changed to fizz_lol with v3.0!

Hi folks!

I bring to you a LoRA model of my beloved Fizz from League of Legends. It still has quite a few kinks that I hope to sort out the next couple of days, but generally it can produce somewhat respectable images. I am still completely new to this stuff, so I hope you'll bear with me.

The LoRA seems to be relatively flexible with different checkpoints.

The LoRA is trained with NSFW in mind, but wasn't my focus yet, so results are very unstable.

Looking forward to see more images from you people!

Versions:

v1.0

This was my first LoRA and I think it is a bit overtrained, so you get very unstable results. Generally would advice to go with v2.0.

Recommended Settings:

  • Checkpoint: Any 2.5D does relatively well (tested with rundiffusionFX25D, Dreamshaper7 or ElegantEntropy_v12)

  • Clip Skip: 1 or 2 (doesn't seem to make a big difference)

  • CFG Scale: 3.5 (anything over 5 seems to be distorting the image a lot)

  • Resolution: 512x512

  • LoRA Weight: 0.7-0.8

  • Hi-Res: Careful with steps and denoising. Works good on 4-5 steps and 0.4-0.45 denoise.

  • No Restore faces

  • Trigger word: Fizz (League of Legends)

Issues:

  • Unstable body proportions

  • Washed out colors

  • Completely unpredictable tentacle hair

  • Hands

  • Feet

v2.0

Generally a lot of improvements in face and body proportions. Tentacle hair is still more of a miss than a hit, but sometimes you get lucky. Will probably try to work on this issue next. "full body" will render feet which actually often look quite decent.

Recommended Settings:

  • Checkpoint: Any 2.5D does relatively well. Using Dreamshaper7 has been a blast with this version.

  • Clip Skip: 2

  • CFG Scale: 5.5-7

  • Resolution: 512x512, 512x768

  • LoRA Weight: 0.6-0.7

  • Hi-Res: Don't go over 0.55 denoise, otherwise you are good to go.

  • No Restore faces

  • Trigger word: Fizz (League of Legends)

Issues:

  • Unstable tentacle hair

  • Unstable hands

v3.0

Improved flexibility of the model and much more stable tentacle hair and hands. Improved NSFW generation.

Recommended Settings:

  • Trigger Word: fizz_lol

    • Additionally use tentacle hair to give the hair generation a slight push into the right direction. I often found a weight of 0.7 is enough.

  • Suggested Weight: 0.6 - 0.8

  • Please refer to the gallery for all other settings, as they can wildly differ depending on prompt, checkpoints and other loras.

NSFW:

NSFW can be triggered by using cetacean penis and/or nsfw in your prompt. My experience with nsfw has been, that it introduces more weight on the base model, which often led to generations that were not resembling Fizz.

items.name: Concordant - General Negative Embedding
items.description:
Concordant is another TE negative I made for myself as an experiment but also again figured others might like it's effects.

It won't increase colour or make things more colourful, but instead average out colours without making the image washed out (so, no hyper contrast colours but also less drab greys unless intentional).

It also does add detail, but in a more neutral way that doesn't override style. The training data has 0 people/animals/direct subjects and instead is based entirely on abstract concepts to push images away from concordant layouts and colours (hence the name). The effects work better on semi-real models, but tests were done over multiple models.

2 types, depending on the training steps, as they both give slightly different results. The 5k one also is likely to generate backgrounds instead of blank/plain/simple ones and that helps me a lot as rarely do I want just a blank colour.

All of the tests are without VAE so some washed out images are due to the models wanting VAE. Also no post processing or fixes.

Curious about my work process? I have summarized it here.

Building a good prompt with my TIs

You're obviously free to experiment, but bear in mind that my TIs are trained with a more or less fixed phrasing, that normally starts with:

"photo of EMBEDDING_NAME, a woman"

So I recommend always starting your prompt like that and then building the rest of the prompt from there. For instance, "photo of (nab0k0va:0.99), a woman as a movie star, modelshoot style, (extremely detailed CG unity 8k wallpaper), photo of the most beautiful artwork in the world, professional majestic oil painting by Ed Blinkey, Atey Ghailan, Studio Ghibli, by Jeremy Mann, Greg Manchess, Antonio Moro, trending on ArtStation, trending on CGSociety, Intricate, High Detail, Sharp focus, dramatic, photorealistic painting art by midjourney and greg rutkowski, (white turtleneck top:1.2), ((movie premiere)), (long skirt), ((standing near a movie theater)), ((paparazzi in the background)), (looking at viewer:1.2), (detailed pupils:1.3), ((closeup portrait:1.1))"

items.name: Bunny Ears Pose
items.description:
Something I'm surprised I haven't seen yet, this should allow whatever character(s) you're generating to truly become bnuuy. Perfect hands not included.

For general usage, I'd recommend a weight of 0.8, but you can raise or lower it without much fuss, as well as the tags arms up and/or rabbit pose.
Arms up will work on it's own, but rabbit pose should be very effective in getting the pose. You can also try to use one arm up, best paired with something for the other hand to do, but I can't guarantee this one will work. It might depend on your checkpoint.

Additionally, if you're not using a character lora (or that lora isn't that strong when it comes to the outfit) you might want to put bunnysuit and bunny ears in the negative prompt, or it could end up altering the outfit.

Due to the common nature of images with the pose, this lora is very effectively trained on bunnysuits, bunny ears, and from front. You can avoid the outfit and ears, like I said above, but the angles are a different matter - in some situations, from [the] side can produce weird results, and it's more likely if the generation isn't trying to point the character's face and hands at the viewer.
From behind has issues with the palms, as it will attempt to face the hands towards the camera. You can inpaint the hands, or use a 2nd pass (potentially with a lower weight) if you're using comfyui, in order to fix them however.

As this was trained on drawn images, I can't guarantee this will work with realistic models, but it should work well with most loras and checkpoints, so long as they don't have an iron rule over the character's arms.

items.name: Michael Cera Lora
items.description:
Be nice, have fun!

Michael Austin Cera (/ˈsɛrə/; Italian: [ˈtʃeːra]; born June 7, 1988)[1] is a Canadian actor. He is known for his awkward, offbeat characters in coming of age comedy films and for portraying George Michael Bluth in the sitcom Arrested Development (2003–2006, 2013, 2018–2019).

He has had numerous roles in United States television and film productions, including character and for his film roles as Evan in Superbad (2007), Paulie Bleeker in Juno (2007), Scott Pilgrim in Scott Pilgrim vs. the World (2010), and a fictional version of himself in This Is the End (2013). Other starring roles include in Nick & Norah's Infinite Playlist (2008), and Youth in Revolt (2009). Cera also has had dramatic roles in Confessions of a Dangerous Mind (2002), Molly's Game (2017), and Gloria Bell (2019). He voiced Dick Grayson/Robin in The Lego Batman Movie (2017), Barry in Sausage Party (2016), and Sal Viscuso, the voice behind the announcements in Childrens Hospital.

Cera is also known for his Broadway performances in the Kenneth Lonergan plays This Is Our Youth in 2014, Lobby Hero in 2018, for which he received a nomination for the Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Play, and The Waverly Gallery in 2019.

In addition to acting, Cera is a musician, having released his debut album True That in 2014. Cera has also performed as the touring bassist for indie rock supergroup Mister Heavenly.
